properties.title: Living Shipwrecks 3D
properties.description: This project provides three-dimensional (3D) visualizations of fish around shipwrecks located on the continental shelf of North Carolina, USA. The data layers within this project include multibeam bathymetry of the shipwrecks, as well as 3D representations of individual fish and schools of fish. Fish were detected with two types of echosounders: 1) splitbeam echosounder and 2) multibeam echosounder. The splitbeam echosounder ensonified fish within a narrow (7-degree) beam width and allowed quantification of individual fish, as well as fish schools. The multibeam echosounder ensonified fish within a broader beam width, permitting visualizations of the broader extent of fish schools.

properties.title: 令和2年7月豪雨
properties.description:
(From Wikipedia)

On 4 July 2020, heavy rain caused flooding in the southern Japanese island of Kyushu. At 5 AM local time(UTC+9) the Japan Meteorological Agency raised its heavy rain warning to its highest level of 3 in many parts of the prefectures, the first time it has ever done so for these areas.[3] The Japan Meteorological Agency stated the amount of rain was record breaking for the region and was never seen before.[4] The rate of rainfall exceeded 100 millimetres (3.9 in) per hour.[5]

As of 6 July 2020, 49 people are confirmed dead.[6] Fourteen of the dead were residents in a flooded old age home in Kuma, Kumamoto.[3][4] Kumamoto governor Ikuo Kabashima stated that scores were stranded after mud and floodwater gushed into the old age home.[1] According to a rescue volunteer, when they reached the old age home the water was still on the first floor level. The rescue personnel managed to rescue residents who had made it up to the second floor but were unable to reach those left below.[5] According to the staff at the home, they roused residents at 5 a.m. and shuffled them upstairs. On the first floor, when water came into the building, they placed residents with wheelchairs on top of tables in the dining room. The staff was unable to rescue the deceased residents after water broke through the windows and the patients floated off the tables.[7][8]

Following overnight rains, authorities instructed over 75,000 residents to evacuate in the prefectures of Kumamoto and Kagoshima.[9] 203,200 residents were instructed to shelter in place, and 109 shelters were opened in the region.[3]

Kamase Bridge (left) and Kumagawa Railway Bridge No.1‎ (right) were washed away.

The Kuma River overran its bank in eleven different locations and breached one levee.[6] A dike was breached near the town of Hitoyoshi, Kumamoto, and it was flooded by the Kuma River.[3][9] In Kuma, Kumamoto, stranded residents were rescued by helicopter.[9] Eight homes were swept away in Ashikita, Kumamoto.[4] In Tsunagi, Kumamoto, 2–3 people were pulled out of a landslide without signs of life.[9] Some 8,000 homes were left without power in Kumamoto and Kagoshima.[9]
properties.snippet: Record-breaking heavy rain hit the prefectures of Kumamoto and Kagoshima in the southern Japanese island of Kyushu on 4 July 2020.

The Florida Environment and Natural History Collections Portal from USF Libraries is your gateway to our vast archival, book, and data collections on the topic. Sources capture the histories of the air, land, and water, offer sources for scholars to tell the stories of how humans and the natural world have interacted for hundreds of years.

Browse the portal to see our newest digitized collections, previews of our physical holdings, and links to scholarly publications on FLENH topics. properties.title: Urban Boundary and Functional Classification Update Process
properties.description:
Urban Areas represent densely developed areas based on population density. The Census revises these urban areas every 10 years based on population counts from the decennial census. Once the Census Bureau has designated new urban areas, the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) gives state DOTs the opportunity to adjust and revise these boundaries to be more consistent with transportation planning needs. Along with Urban Boundary designation, FHWA also recommends that states review the functional classification of their roadway system every 10 years, and that the review be completed within three years of approval by FHWA of the adjusted urban boundaries.

This website will host the District Urban Boundary and Functional Classification data to be adjusted.

Point of Contact: Jerry Scott and Joel Worrell.
properties.snippet: On a decennial basis (every 10 years) following every Census, FDOT in coordination with FHWA and local partners are required to update Urban Boundary and Functional Classification for the State of Florida.

properties.title: Port Hamilton Refining and Transporation (PHRT) Public Hub Site
properties.description:
On December 5, 2022, EPA entered into a legal agreement requiring Port Hamilton Refining and Transportation LLLP (PHRT) to hire experts to safely remove chemicals that are not being properly managed at the facility in equipment that EPA had identified as being of concern after an EPA inspection. The Order on Consent requires full access for EPA to be on site to oversee the work and safety measures in the short-term until the chemicals are removed or secured.

On February 9, 2023, EPA conditionally approved plans to safely remove dangerous chemicals from systems at the refinery on St. Croix. EPA will oversee the work, which will begin with preparation work starting in February. Repairs to the ammonia system are scheduled to begin in early March, and chemical removal is scheduled to begin in early April and expected to be complete sometime this summer.

EPA will oversee the work to remove the chemicals and will conduct around-the-clock air monitoring to ensure people’s safety.

Further details of the work to be performed can be found here.

properties.title: Urban Boundary and Functional Classification Update Process
properties.description:
Urban Areas represent densely developed areas based on population density. The Census revises these urban areas every 10 years based on population counts from the decennial census. Once the Census Bureau has designated new urban areas, the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) gives state DOTs the opportunity to adjust and revise these boundaries to be more consistent with transportation planning needs. Along with Urban Boundary designation, FHWA also recommends that states review the functional classification of their roadway system every 10 years, and that the review be completed within three years of approval by FHWA of the adjusted urban boundaries.

This website will host the District Urban Boundary and Functional Classification data to be adjusted.

Point of Contact: Jerry Scott and Joel Worrell.
properties.snippet: On a decennial basis (every 10 years) following every Census, FDOT in coordination with FHWA and local partners are required to update Urban Boundary and Functional Classification for the State of Florida.
